Final Project Notebook: Presidential Debate Analysis¶

Due Date: 5/13/2020¶

Intro/Problem Statement: Words are extremely powerful, especially when they are used over and over again to persuade the audience and ingrain the words into their memories. Our final project will analyze the debate speeches of Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump during the 2016 presidential race. The objective of the project aims at identifying what words and phrases were most common and looks into how both candidates’ word choices shaped the discussions during the debates. To take it a step further we analyzed how each candidate talks and gave the program data from other notable Democrats and Republicans to see if the program can find connections based on how these people speak.¶

Our grade targets for the project are the following:¶

a. Low Target: Use TF-IDF scores to analyze the frequency of the most common words used for both candidates and how they may have influenced the election.¶

b. Medium Target: Use TF-IDF scores to analyze the frequency of the most common words used for both candidates and how they may have influenced the election. In addition, use the data to train the program to see how well it can predict how each individual talks during some of their other speeches outside the debate arena. To do this we will use the text collection we made of both candidates, then we will use KNN search on the data to find the nearest neighbors and look for patterns.¶

c. High Target: Use TF-IDF scores to analyze the frequency of the most common words used for both candidates and how they may have influenced the election. In addition, use the data to train the program to see how well it can predict how each individual talks during some of their other speeches outside the debate arena. To take it a step further we could also find how each candidate talks and give the program data from other notable Democrats and Republicans and see if the program can find connections based on how these people speak. We will run both Euclidean classify and Cosine classify and compare the results to see which is a more accurate predictor of a person’s party.¶

We attempted all of the following grade targets in this project¶

In [7]:
all_docs = []
stemmer = nltk.stem.porter.PorterStemmer()

for line in text:
    lowered = line.lower()
    fixed = lowered.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(fixed)
    tokens = [w for w in tokens if not w in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')]
    for i in range(len(tokens)):
        tokens[i] = stemmer.stem(tokens[i])
   
    all_docs.append(tokens)

num_docs = len(all_docs)

print('Processed', num_docs, 'lines.')
print('Example: ',all_docs[0])

For this part we designed a matrix using TF-IDF scores so that we could anaylze the frequency of the terms used. This will allow us to figure out what some of the key words were throughout the debate and possibly help see how the debate was shaped. The TF-IDF score is used to see how often words appear together in documents as well as how often they appear. It gives them a score for each pairing of word and document. We should be able to find the most important words using this method.¶

In [10]:
# Compute a term-document matrix such that td_matrix[id][term]

TD = np.zeros((num_docs, num_terms))
# Note that there are a couple ways to speed this next part up,
# but they sacrifice clarity for speed.
# Loop through each document
for i in range(num_docs):
    # Loop through each term
    for j in range(num_terms):
    # Grab the current document from the list of all the documents
        doc = all_docs[i]
    # Grab the current term from the list of all the unique terms
        if len(doc) != 0:
            term = unique_terms[j]
    # Calculate the TF-IDF score for the current term and document
    # and store it in the TD array
            TD[i, j] = tc.tf_idf(term, doc)
TD

In [28]:
clinton_text = clinton_df['Text']
clinton_docs = []
stemmer = nltk.stem.porter.PorterStemmer()

for line in clinton_text:
    lowered = line.lower()
    fixed = lowered.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(fixed)
    tokens = [w for w in tokens if not w in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')]
    for i in range(len(tokens)):
        tokens[i] = stemmer.stem(tokens[i])
   
    clinton_docs.append(tokens)

num_clinton_docs = len(clinton_docs)

print('Processed', num_clinton_docs, 'lines.')
print('Example: ',trump_docs[0])

clinton_TD = np.zeros((num_clinton_docs, num_terms))
# Loop through each document
for i in range(num_clinton_docs):
    # Loop through each term
    for j in range(num_terms):
    # Grab the current document from the list of all the documents
        doc = clinton_docs[i]
        if len(doc) != 0:
    # Grab the current term from the list of all the unique terms
            term = clinton_unique_terms[j]
    # Calculate the TF-IDF score for the current term and document
    # and store it in the TD array
            clinton_TD[i, j] = clinton_tc.tf_idf(term, doc)
print('TD matrix created.')
print('The columns correspond to the terms:')
print(clinton_unique_terms)
print('\nThe first document has these TD-IDF scores:')
print(clinton_TD[0, :])

In [43]:
def convert_doc_string_to_terms(doc):
    stemmer = nltk.stem.porter.PorterStemmer()
    # Make lowercase
    lowered = doc.lower()
    # Remove punctuation
    fixed = lowered.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    # Tokenize (splitting on whitespace, plus a few extras)
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(fixed)
    # Remove stop words
    nonstop = []
    for w in tokens:
        if w not in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english'):
            nonstop.append(w)

    tokens = []
    for w in nonstop:
        tokens.append(stemmer.stem(w))
    # Add the current list of tokens to the list of all the lists of tokens
    
    return  tokens
In [44]:
def cos_sim(x, y):
    if vector_norm(x) == 0 or vector_norm(y) == 0:
        return 0
    else:
        return x.dot(y) / ((vector_norm(x) * vector_norm(y)))
In [45]:
def vector_norm(x):
    return np.sqrt(np.sum(np.power(x, 2)))

This function performs knn search and has options for finding Euclidean, manhattan, or cosine distances.¶

In [46]:
def knn_search(x, D, K, measure):
    
    if measure == 0:
        # euclidean distances from the other points
        dists = np.sqrt(((D - x)**2).sum(axis=1))
    elif measure == 1:
        # manhattan distances from the other points
        dists = (np.abs(D-x)).sum(axis=1)
    elif measure == 2:
        #cosine distance
        dists = np.zeros(len(D))
        count = 0
        for trainExamp in D:
            distance = 1 - cos_sim(x,trainExamp)
            dists[count] = distance
            count = count + 1
    # This line finds the indexes of the sorted distances.
    idx = np.argsort(dists) # sorting
    # return the indexes of K nearest neighbors and the distances
    return idx[:K], dists

The classify function will find the distances above and uses the tf-idf scores to try and predict the labels using the test data as a reference¶

In [48]:
def classify(K, metric):
    
    correct_predictions = 0
    examp_count = 0
    for example, label in zip(test_data, test_label):
        example_terms = convert_doc_string_to_terms(example)
        
    
        test_scores = np.zeros(len(unique_terms))
        count = 0
       
        #TF-IDF scores
        for i in range(0,len(unique_terms)):
            test_scores[i] = tc.tf_idf(unique_terms[i], example_terms)

            
        # knn search
        neighbor_idx, distances = knn_search(test_scores, TD, K, metric)
    
        
        neigh_labels = train_label[neighbor_idx]
        

        label_count = Counter(neigh_labels)

        avg_neighbor_rating = int(round(neigh_labels.mean()))

        examp_count = examp_count + 1
        if avg_neighbor_rating == label:
            correct_predictions = correct_predictions + 1
        
    return correct_predictions/examp_count

Below are the different forms of classify for different values of K. A graph is displayed for each of the values of K and the mean is calculated. For both methods the means were below 50% which is worse than a coin flip. This is likely due to the fact that the candidates likely do not speak similarly to the other candidates of their party that year. Although our program did not accurately predict policital speech at an efficient level, we believe that we achieved the high target as we ran each analyses we laid out and came up with definitive data that, with more time, could be improved and expanded upon.¶

Some of the early analytics we ran were simple word totaling aimed at giving insight as to whether or not the most repeated words throughout the debates for each candidate and overall shaped the outcome of the election in any way.¶

One graph we created showed the most common words used by Trump during the three debates. The top 3 words all appear at the top of the most common words overall. He does say the word "bad" and "deal" the same number of times which likely means they were stated together and was one of his talking points. During the campaign, Trump attempted to tarnish the Clintons' reputation by questioning a lot of decisionmaking that she and her husband made while working in the Whitehouse and Senate respectively. He also appears to mention Obama a large amount but overall the results do not differ greatly.¶

The graph displaying Hillary Clinton's top 50 most commonly used words produced similarly bland results. The top 3 words are not surprising, however, it is interesting that the word "go" is only Clinton's third most used word even though it is the most used word overall. Most of the words used seem common throughout the debate such as people, women, and tax are common throughout. There do appear to be less negative words used by Clinton than by Trump.¶

We found that there we 2425 unique words spoken. We also looked at what the longest words were that were spoken. Unfortunately, there were not many interesting results for the long words. The longest word was Pennsylvania with the next being African-American. Most of the long words are fairly commonly used terms so these likely did not influence the debate.¶

We found that Hillary Clinton used 1798 unique words while Trump only used 1562. This is quite interesting as it may have benefited trump to repeat words, phrases, and ideas and his slightly less expansive vocabulary could have contributed to the simplicity and ease of understandability of his message to his potential voter-base.¶

We also created a term document matrix of the top 80 words used among all the lines of text, and it produced much more interesting results than the most commonly used words. We see the appearance of words that likely shaped the debates. "Thank" appears a lot in certain documents but that is to be expected. We also see a lot more negative words used here such as "cant", "stolen", and "fire". Based on this you can also clearly see "build" and "Mexico" commonly appear in the same document which was a topic used during these debates and was something Trump ran his campaign on.¶

We then moved into the machine learning aspect of the project by running cosine and euclidean distance matrices on the training data (data from the three 2016 presidential debates) and the new test data compiled of other speeches of Hillary and Trump combined with other prominent politicians from both sides of the aisle such as Bernie Sanders, Ted Cruz, Marco Rubio, etc. It is safe to say that the program predicted who said what at a higher rate when we fed in text from just Trump and Clinton from other debates (.61 for Euclidean and .59 for Cosine). However, when we threw other politicians into the mix with completely different speech patterns, vocabulary, adgendas and platforms, the program had a slightly more difficult time accurately predicting (.48 for Euclidean and .54 for cosine).¶

We performed different forms of classification for different values of K. A graph was displayed for each of the values of K and the mean is calculated. For both methods the means were around 50% which is not much better than a coin flip. This is likely due to the fact that the candidates likely do not speak similarly to the other candidates of their party that year. We believe that this data shows that Trump and Hillary were not very representative of the candidates in 2016 which is likely why the means were so low and even worse than if the program was flipping a coin. One potential issue is that the data is not very representative of either candidate or the test data does not have enough rows of data.¶¶

In our experience of working on the project, clustering did not work as well as we would have liked because it did not seem to find the proper buckets for each text document. A possible solution could be normalizing the data before running K means.¶

Another issue was the test data for other candidates. As explained above, the program was not able to predict what side of the aisle they are on. One solution could be to either take more data from each of the candidates for the train and test data.¶

One issue we ran into was in regards to formatting the different matrices to make them easy to read.¶

Overall we believe we have sucessfully accomplished all the tasks we set out to do with the high target section.¶
